\pard\nowidctlpar\fi397\qj\par
CALLAHAN WAS IRRITATED when he knocked on the door to Darby's apartment. He was quite perturbed and had a lot on his mind, a lot that he wanted to say, but he knew better than to start a fight because there was something he wanted much worse than to blow off a little steam. She had avoided him for four days now while she played detective and barricaded herself in the law library. She had skipped classes and failed to return his calls, and in general neglected him during his hour of crisis. But he knew when she opened the door he would smile and forget about being neglected. \par
\par
He held a liter of wine and a real pizza from Mama Rosa's. It was after ten, Saturday night. He knocked again, and looked up and down the street at the neat duplexes and bungalows. The chain rattled from inside, and he instantly smiled. The neglect vanished.\par
\par
"Who is it?" she asked through the chain.\par
\par
"Thomas Callahan, remember? I'm at your door begging you to let me in so we can play and be friends again." \par
\par
The door opened and Callahan stepped in. She took the wine and pecked him on the cheek. "Are we still buddies?" he asked.\par
\par
"Yes, Thomas. I've been busy." He followed her through the cluttered den to the kitchen. A computer and an assortment of thick books covered the table.\par
\par
"I called. Why didn't you call me back?"\par
\par
"I've been out," she said, opening a drawer and removing a corkscrew.\par
\par
"You've got a machine. I've been talking to it."\par
\par
"Are you trying to fight, Thomas?" \par
\par
He looked at her bare legs. "No! I swear I'm not mad. I promise. Please forgive me if I appear to be upset."\par
\par
"Stop it."\par
\par
"When can we go to bed?"\par
\par
"Are you sleepy?"\par
\par
"Anything but. Come on, Darby, it's been three nights."\par
\par
"Five. What kind of pizza?" She removed the cork and poured two glasses. Callahan watched every move.\par
\par
"Oh, it's one of those Saturday night specials where they throw on everything headed for the garbage. Shrimp tails, eggs, crawfish heads. Cheap wine too. I'm a little low on cash, and I'm leaving town tomorrow so I have to watch what I spend, and since I'm leaving I thought I'd just come on over and get laid tonight so I wouldn't be tempted by some contagious woman in D.C. What do you think?" \par
\par
Darby was opening the pizza box. "Looks like sausage and peppers."\par
\par
"Can I still get laid?"\par
\par
"Maybe later. Drink your wine and let's chat. We haven't had a long talk in a while."\par
\par
"I have. I've been talking to your machine all week." \par
\par
He took his wineglass and the bottle and followed her closely to the den, where she turned on the stereo. They relaxed on the sofa.\par
\par
"Let's get drunk," he said.\par
\par
"You're so romantic."\par
\par
"I've got some romance for you."\par
\par
"You've been drunk for a week."\par
\par
"No I haven't. Eighty percent of a week. It's your fault for avoiding me."\par
\par
"What's wrong with you, Thomas?"\par
\par
"I've got the shakes. I'm all keyed up and I need companionship to knock the edge off. Whatta you say?"\par
\par
"Let's get half drunk." She sipped her wine and draped her legs across his lap. He held his breath as if in pain.\par
\par
"What time is your flight?" she asked. \par
\par
He was gulping now. "One-thirty. Nonstop to National. I'm supposed to register at five, and there's a dinner at eight. After that I may be forced to roam the streets looking for love." \par
\par
She smiled. "Okay, okay. We'll do it in a minute. But let's talk first." \par
\par
Callahan breathed a sigh of relief. "I can talk for ten minutes, then I'll just collapse."\par
\par
"What's up for Monday?"\par
\par
"The usual eight hours of airhead debate on the future of the Fifth Amendment, then a committee will draft a proposed conference report that no one will approve. More debate Tuesday, another report, perhaps an altercation or two, then we adjourn with nothing accomplished and go home. I'll be in late Tuesday evening, and I'd like a date at a very nice restaurant, after which we can go back to my place for an intellectual discussion and animal sex. Where's the pizza?"\par
\par
"In there. I'll get it." \par
\par
He was stroking her legs. "Don't move. I'm not the least bit hungry."\par
\par
"Why do you go to these conferences?"\par
\par
"I'm a member, and I'm a professor, and we're just sort of expected to roam the country attending meetings with other educated idiots and adopting reports nobody reads. If I didn't go, the dean would think I was not contributing to the academic environment." \par
\par
She refilled the wineglasses. "You're uptight, Thomas."\par
\par
"I know. It's been a rough week. I hate the thought of a bunch of Neanderthals rewriting the Constitution. We'll live in a police state in ten years. I can't do anything about it, so I'll probably resort to alcohol." \par
\par
Darby sipped slowly and watched him. The music was soft and the lights low. "I'm getting a buzz," she said.\par
\par
"That's about right for you. A glass and a half and you're history. If you were Irish you could drink all night."\par
\par
"My father was half Scottish."\par
\par
"Not good enough." Callahan crossed his feet on the coffee table and relaxed. He gently rubbed her ankles. "Can I paint your toes?" \par
\par
She said nothing. He had a fetish for her toes, and insisted on doing the nails with bright red polish at least twice a month. They'd seen it in Bull Durham, and though he wasn't as neat and sober as Kevin Costner, she had grown to enjoy the intimacy of it.\par
\par
"No toes tonight?" he asked.\par
\par
"Maybe later. You look tired."\par
\par
"I'm relaxing, but I'm filled with virile male electricity, and you will not put me off by telling me I look tired."\par
\par
"Have some more wine." \par
\par
Callahan had more wine, and sank deeper in the sofa. "So, Ms. Shaw, who done it?"\par
\par
"Professionals. Haven't you read the papers?"\par
\par
"Of course. But who's behind the professionals?"\par
\par
"I don't know. After last night, the unanimous choice seems to be the Underground Army."\par
\par
"But you're not convinced."\par
\par
"No. There have been no arrests. I'm not convinced."\par
\par
"And you've got some obscure suspect unknown to the rest of the country."\par
\par
"I had one, but now I'm not so sure. I spent three days tracking it down, even summarized it all real nice and neat in my little computer, and printed out a thin rough draft of a brief which I have now discarded." \par
\par
Callahan stared at her. "You're telling me you skipped classes for three days, ignored me, worked around the clock playing Sherlock Holmes, and now you're throwing it away."\par
\par
"It's over there on the table."\par
\par
"I can't believe this. While I sulked around in loneliness all week, I knew it was for a worthy cause. I knew my suffering was for the good of the country because you would peel away the onion and tell me tonight or perhaps tomorrow who done it."\par
\par
"It can't be done, at least not with legal research. There's no pattern, no common thread in the murders. I almost burned up the computers at the law school."\par
\par
"Ha! I told you so. You forget, dear, that I am a genius at constitutional law, and I knew immediately that Rosenberg and Jensen had nothing in common but black robes and death threats. The Nazis or Aryans or Kluxers or Mafia or some other group killed them because Rosenberg was Rosenberg, and because Jensen was the easiest target and somewhat of an embarrassment."\par
\par
"Well, why don't you call the FBI and share your insights with them? I'm sure they're sitting by the phone."\par
\par
\par
"Don't be angry. I'm sorry. Please forgive me."\par
\par
"You're an ass, Thomas."\par
\par
"Yes, but you love me, don't you?"\par
\par
"I don't know."\par
\par
"Can we still go to bed? You promised."\par
\par
"We'll see." \par
\par
Callahan placed his glass on the table, and attacked her. "Look, baby. I'll read your brief, okay. And then we'll talk about it, okay. But I'm not thinking clearly right now, and I won't be able to continue until you take my weak and trembling hand and lead me to your bed."\par
\par
"Forget my little brief."\par
\par
"Please, dammit, Darby, please." \par
\par
She grabbed his neck and pulled him to her. They kissed long and hard, a wet, almost violent kiss. \par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi397\qc *  *  *\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi397\qj\par
THE COP stuck his thumb on the button next to the name of Gray Grantham, and held it down for twenty seconds. Then a brief pause. Then another twenty seconds. Pause. Twenty seconds. Pause. Twenty seconds. He thought this was funny because Grantham was a night owl and had probably slept less than three or four hours, and now all this incessant buzzing echoing throughout his hallway. He pushed again and looked at his patrol car parked illegally on the curb under the streetlight. It was almost dawn, Sunday, and the street was empty. Twenty seconds. Pause. Twenty seconds. \par
\par
Maybe Grantham was dead. Or maybe he was comatose from booze and a late night on the town. Maybe he had someone's woman up there and had no plans to answer the door. Pause. Twenty seconds. \par
\par
The mike crackled. "Who is it!"\par
\par
"Police!" answered the cop, who was black and emphasized the po in police just for the fun of it.\par
\par
"What do you want?" Grantham demanded.\par
\par
"Maybe I gotta warrant." The cop was near laughter. \par
\par
Grantham's voice softened, and he sounded wounded. "Is this Cleve?"\par
\par
"It is."\par
\par
"What time is it, Cleve?"\par
\par
"Almost five-thirty."\par
\par
"It must be good."\par
\par
"Don't know. Sarge didn't say, you know. He just said to wake you up 'cause he wanted to talk."\par
\par
"Why does he always want to talk before the sun comes up?"\par
\par
"Stupid question, Grantham." \par
\par
A slight pause. "Yeah, I guess so. I presume he wants to talk right now."\par
\par
"No. You got thirty minutes. He said be there at six."\par
\par
"Where?"\par
\par
"There's a little coffee shop on Fourteenth near the Trinidad Playground. It's dark and safe, and Sarge likes it."\par
\par
"Where does he find these places?"\par
\par
"You know, for a reporter you can ask the dumbest questions. The name of the place is Glenda's, and I suggest you get going or you'll be late."\par
\par
"Will you be there?"\par
\par
"I'll drop in, just to make sure you're okay."\par
\par
"I thought you said it was safe."\par
\par
"It is safe, for that part of town. Can you find it?"\par
\par
"Yeah. I'll be there as soon as I can."\par
\par
"Have a nice day, Grantham." \par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi397\qc *  *  *\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi397\qj\par
SARGE WAS OLD, very black, with a head full of brilliant white hair that sprang out in all directions. He wore thick sunglasses whenever he was awake, and most of his coworkers in the West Wing of the White House thought he was half blind. He held his head sideways and smiled like Ray Charles. He sometimes bumped into door facings and desks as he unloaded trash cans and dusted furniture. He walked slowly and gingerly as if counting his steps. He worked patiently, always with a smile, always with a kind word for anyone willing to give him one. For the most part he was ignored and dismissed as just another friendly, old, partially disabled black janitor. \par
\par
Sarge could see around corners. His territory was the West Wing, where he had been cleaning for thirty years now. Cleaning and listening. Cleaning and seeing. He picked up after some terribly important people who were often too busy to watch their words, especially in the presence of poor old Sarge. \par
\par
He knew which doors stayed open, and which walls were thin, and which air vents carried sound. He could disappear in an instant, then reappear in a shadow where the terribly important people could not see him. \par
\par
He kept most of it to himself. But from time to time, he fell heir to a juicy bit of information that could be pieced together with another one, and Sarge would make the judgment call that it should be repeated. He was very careful. He had three years until retirement, and he took no chances. \par
\par
No one ever suspected Sarge of leaking stories to the press. There were usually enough big mouths within any White House to lay blame on each other. It was hilarious, really. Sarge would talk to Grantham at the Post, then wait excitedly for the story, then listen to the wailing in the basement when the heads rolled. \par
\par
He was an impeccable source, and he talked only to Grantham. His son Cleve, the cop, arranged the meetings, always at odd hours at dark and inconspicuous places. Sarge wore his sunglasses. Grantham wore the same with a hat or cap of some sort. Cleve usually sat with them and watched the crowd. \par
\par
Grantham arrived at Glenda's a few minutes after six, and walked to a booth in the rear. There were three other customers. Glenda herself was frying eggs on a grill near the register. Cleve sat on a stool watching her. \par
\par
They shook hands. A cup of coffee had been poured for Grantham.\par
\par
"Sorry I'm late," he said.\par
\par
"No problem, my friend. Good to see you." Sarge had a raspy voice that was difficult to suppress with a whisper. No one was listening. \par
\par
Grantham gulped coffee. "Busy week at the White House."\par
\par
"You could say that. Lot of excitement. Lot of happiness."\par
\par
"You don't say." Grantham could not take notes at these meetings. It would be too obvious, Sarge said when he laid the ground rules.\par
\par
"Yes. The President and his boys were elated with the news of Justice Rosenberg. This made them very happy."\par
\par
"What about Justice Jensen?"\par
\par
"Well, as you noticed, the President attended the memorial service, but did not speak. He had planned to give a eulogy, but backed out because he would have been saying nice things about a gay fella."\par
\par
"Who wrote the eulogy?"\par
\par
"The speechwriters. Mainly Mabry. Worked on it all day Thursday, then he backed out."\par
\par
"He also went to Rosenberg's service."\par
\par
"Yes, he did. But he didn't want to. Said he'd rather go to hell for a day. But in the end, he chickened out and went anyway. He's quite happy Rosenberg was murdered. There was almost a festive mood around the place Wednesday. Fate has dealt him a wonderful hand. He now gets to restructure the Court, and he's very excited about this." \par
\par
Grantham listened hard. Sarge continued.\par
\par
"There's a short list of nominees. The original had twenty or so names, then it was cut to eight."\par
\par
"Who did the cutting?"\par
\par
Who do you think? The President and Fletcher Coal. They're terrified of leaks at this point. Evidently the list is nothing but young conservative judges, most of whom are obscure."\par
\par
"Any names?"\par
\par
"Just two. A certain man named Pryce from Idaho, and one named MacLawrence from Vermont. That's all I know about names. I think they are both federal judges. Nothing more on this."\par
\par
"What about the investigation?"\par
\par
"I haven't heard much, but as usual I'll keep my ears open. There doesn't appear to be much going on."\par
\par
"Anything else?"\par
\par
"No. When will you run it?"\par
\par
"In the morning."\par
\par
"It'll be fun."\par
\par
"Thanks, Sarge." \par
\par
The sun was up now and the cafe was noisier. Cleve strolled over and sat next to his father. "You guys about finished?"\par
\par
"We are," Sarge said. \par
\par
Cleve glanced around. "I think we need to leave. Grantham goes first, I'll follow, then Pop here can stay as long as he wants."\par
\par
"Mighty nice of you," Sarge said.\par
\par
"Thanks, fellas," Grantham said as he headed for the door. \par
\par
