GAVIN QUIT THE BARS SUNDAY. He was getting nowhere. She had called him, and she was not hanging around those places, so what the hell. He was drinking too much and eating too much, and he was tired of New Orleans. He already had a flight booked for late Monday afternoon, and if she didn't call again he was finished playing detective. \par
\par
He couldn't find her, and it wasn't his fault. Cabdrivers got lost in this city. Voyles would be screaming by noon. He had done his best. \par
\par
He was stretched on the bed in nothing but boxer shorts, flipping through a magazine and ignoring the television. It was almost eleven. He would wait on her until twelve, then try to sleep. \par
\par
It rang at exactly eleven. He pushed a button and remotely killed the television. "Hello." \par
\par
"It was her.It's me, Gavin."\par
\par
"So you're alive."\par
\par
"Barely." \par
\par
He sat on the edge of the bed. "What's happened?"\par
\par
"They saw me today, and one of their goons, my friend Stump, chased me through the Quarter. You haven't met Stump, but he's the one who watched you and everyone else walk into the chapel."\par
\par
"But you got away."\par
\par
"Yeah. A small miracle, but I got away."\par
\par
"What happened to Stump?"\par
\par
"He was mortally wounded. He's probably lying in a bed somewhere wearing an ice pack in his shorts. He was just a few steps from me when he picked a fight with the wrong guys. I'm scared, Gavin."\par
\par
"Did he follow you from somewhere?"\par
\par
"No. We just sort of met on the street." \par
\par
Verheek paused a second. Her voice was shaking, but under control. She was losing her cool. "Look, Darby. I've got a flight out of here tomorrow afternoon. I have this little job and my boss expects me to be at the office. So I can't hang around New Orleans for the next month hoping you don't get killed and hoping you come to your senses and trust me. I'm leaving tomorrow, and I think you need to go with me."\par
\par
"Go where?"\par
\par
"To Washington. To my house. To someplace other than where you are."\par
\par
"What happens then?"\par
\par
"Well, you get to live, for one thing. I'll plead with the Director, and I promise you'll be safe. We'll do something, dammit. Anything beats this."\par
\par
"What makes you think we can just fly out of here?"\par
\par
"Because we'll have three FBI agents surrounding you. Because I'm not a complete dumbass. Look, Darby, tell me where you want to meet right now, and within fifteen minutes I'll come get you with three agents. These guys have guns, and they're not afraid of your little Stump and his pals. We'll get you out of the city tonight, and take you to Washington tomorrow. I promise you'll personally meet my boss, the Honorable F. Denton Voyles, tomorrow, and we'll go from there."\par
\par
"I thought the FBI was not involved."\par
\par
"It's not involved, but it may be."\par
\par
"Then where do the three agents come from?"\par
\par
"I've got friends." \par
\par
She thought for a moment, and her voice was suddenly stronger. "Behind your hotel is a place called Riverwalk. It's a shopping area with restaurants and"\par
\par
"I spent two hours there this afternoon."\par
\par
"Good. On the second level is a clothing store called Frenchmen's Bend."\par
\par
"I saw it."\par
\par
"At precisely noon tomorrow, I want you to stand by the entrance, and wait for five minutes."\par
\par
"Come on, Darby. You won't be alive at noon tomorrow. Enough of this cat and mouse."\par
\par
"Just do as I say, Gavin. We've never met, so I have no idea what you look like. Wear a black shirt of some type and a red baseball cap."\par
\par
"Where might I find such articles?"\par
\par
"Just get them."\par
\par
"Okay, okay, I'll have them. I guess you want me to pick my nose with a shovel or something. This is silly."\par
\par
"I'm not in a silly mood, and if you don't shut up we'll call it off."\par
\par
"It's your neck."\par
\par
"Please, Gavin."\par
\par
"I'm sorry. I'll do whatever you say. That's a very busy spot to be."\par
\par
"Yes, it is. I just feel safer in a crowd. Stand by the door for five minutes or so, and hold a folded newspaper. I'll be watching. After five minutes, walk inside the store, and go to the right rear corner where there's a rack of safari jackets. Browse around a bit, and I'll find you."\par
\par
"And what might you be wearing?"\par
\par
"Don't worry about me."\par
\par
"Fine. Then what do we do?"\par
\par
"You and I, and only you and I, will leave the city. I don't want anyone else to know of this. Do you understand?"\par
\par
"No, I don't understand. I can arrange security."\par
\par
"No, Gavin. I'm the boss, okay. No one else. Forget your three agent friends. Agreed?"\par
\par
"Agreed. How do you propose we leave the city?"\par
\par
"I've got a plan for that too."\par
\par
"I don't like any of your plans, Darby. These thugs are breathing down your neck, and now you're getting me in the middle of it. This is not what I wanted. It's much safer to do it my way. Safer for you, safer for me."\par
\par
"But you'll be there at noon, won't you?" \par
\par
He stood by the bed and spoke with his eyes closed. "Yes. I'll be there. I just hope you make it."\par
\par
"How tall are you?"\par
\par
"Five-ten."\par
\par
"How much do you weigh?"\par
\par
"I was afraid of this. I usually lie, you know. Two hundred, but I plan to lose it. I swear."\par
\par
"I'll see you tomorrow, Gavin."\par
\par
"I hope I see you, dear." \par
\par
She was gone. He hung up. "Son of a bitch!" he yelled to the walls. "Son of a bitch!" He walked along the end of the bed a few times, then to the bathroom, where he closed the door and turned on the shower. \par
\par
He cussed her in the shower for ten minutes, then stepped out, and dried himself. It was more like two hundred and fifteen pounds, and all of it was situated badly on the five-nine frame. It was painful to look at. Here he was, about to meet this gorgeous woman who suddenly trusted him with her life, and what a slob he was. \par
\par
He opened the door. The room was dark. Dark? He had left on the lights. What the hell? He headed for the switch next to the dresser. \par
\par
The first blow crushed his larynx. It was a perfect blow that came from the side, somewhere near the wall. He grunted painfully and fell to one knee, which made the second blow so easy, like an ax on a fat log. It hit like a rock at the base of the skull, and Gavin was dead. \par
\par
Khamel flipped on a light, and looked at the pitiful nude figure frozen on the floor. He was not one to admire his work. He didn't want carpet burns, so he lifted the pudgy corpse onto his shoulders and laid it across the bed. Working quickly without any wasted motion, Khamel turned on the television and raised it to full volume, unzipped his bag, removed a cheap.25 caliber automatic, and placed it precisely on the right temple of the late Gavin Verheek. He covered the gun and the head with two pillows, and pulled the trigger. Now the critical part: he took one pillow and placed it under the head, threw the other one on the floor, and carefully curled the fingers of the right hand around the pistol, leaving it twelve inches from the head. \par
\par
He took the recorder from under the bed, and ran the telephone wire directly into the wall. He punched a button, listened, and there she was. He turned off the television. \par
\par
Every job was different. He had once stalked his prey for three weeks in Mexico City, then caught him in bed with two prostitutes. It was a dumb mistake, and during his career he had been assisted by numerous dumb mistakes by the opposition. This guy was a dumb mistake, a stupid lawyer pilfering around running his mouth, passing out cards with his room number on the back. He had stuck his nose into the world of big-league killing, and look at him now. \par
\par
With a little luck, the cops would look around the room for a few minutes and declare it to be another suicide. They would go through the motions and ask themselves a couple of questions they could not answer, but there were always some of those. Because he was an important FBI lawyer, an autopsy would be done in a day or so, and probably by Tuesday an examiner would suddenly discover it was not a suicide. \par
\par
By Tuesday, the girl would be dead and he would be in Managua. \par
\par
