\pard\nowidctlpar\fi397\qj\par
RUPERT PICKED THEM UP as they turned out of Parklane's driveway. The rented Pontiac was flying all over the street. He drove like an idiot just to keep up, then radioed ahead. \par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi397\qc *  *  *\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi397\qj\par
MATTHEW BARR had never experienced a speedboat before, and after five hours of a bone-jarring voyage through the ocean he was soaked and in pain. His body was numb, and when he saw land he said a prayer, the first in decades. Then he resumed his nonstop cursing of Fletcher Coal. \par
\par
They docked at a small marina near a city that he believed to be Freeport. The captain had said something about Freeport to the man known as Larry when they left Florida. No other word was spoken during the ordeal. Larry's role in the journey was uncertain. He was at least six-six, with a neck as thick as a utility pole, and he did nothing but watch Barr, which was okay at first but after five hours became quite a nuisance. \par
\par
They stood awkwardly when the boat stopped. Larry was the first one out, and he motioned for Barr to join him. Another large man was approaching on the pier, and together they escorted Barr to a waiting van. The van was suspiciously short of windows. \par
\par
At this point, Barr preferred to say good-bye to his new pals, and simply disappear in the direction of Freeport. He'd catch a plane to D.C., and slap Coal the moment he saw his shining forehead. But he had to be cool. They wouldn't dare hurt him. \par
\par
The van stopped moments later at a small airstrip, and Barr was escorted to a black Lear. He admired it briefly before following Larry up the steps. He was cool and relaxed; just another job. After all, he was at one time one of the best CIA agents in Europe. He was an ex-Marine. He could take care of himself. \par
\par
He sat by himself in the cabin. The windows were covered, and this annoyed him. But he understood. Mr. Mattiece treasured his privacy, and Barr could certainly respect that. Larry and the other heavyweight were at the front of the cabin, flipping through magazines and completely ignoring him. \par
\par
Thirty minutes after takeoff, the Lear began its descent, and Larry lumbered toward him.\par
\par
"Put this on," he demanded as he handed over a thick, cloth blindfold. At this point, a rookie would panic. An amateur would start asking questions. But Barr had been blindfolded before, and while he was having serious doubts about this mission, he calmly took the blindfold and covered his eyes. \par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi397\qc *  *  *\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi397\qj\par
THE MAN who removed the blindfold introduced himself as Emil, an assistant to Mr. Mattiece. He was a small, wiry type with dark hair and a thin mustache winding around the lip. He sat in a chair four feet away and lit a cigarette.\par
\par
"Our people tell us you are legitimate, sort of," he said with a friendly smile. Barr looked around the room. There were no walls, only windows in small panes. The sun was bright and pierced his eyes. A plush garden surrounded a series of fountains and pools outside the room. They were in the rear of a very large house.\par
\par
"I'm here on behalf of the President," Barr said.\par
\par
"We believe you." Emil nodded. He was undoubtedly a Cajun.\par
\par
"May I ask who you are?" Barr said.\par
\par
"I'm Emil, and that's enough. Mr. Mattiece is not feeling well. Perhaps you should leave your message with me."\par
\par
"I have orders to speak directly to him."\par
\par
"Orders from Mr. Coal, I believe." Emil never stopped smiling.\par
\par
"That's correct."\par
\par
"I see. Mr. Mattiece prefers not to meet you. He wants you to talk to me." \par
\par
Barr shook his head. Now, if push came to shove, if things got out of hand, then he would gladly talk to Emil if it was necessary. But for now, he would hold firm.\par
\par
"I am not authorized to talk to anyone but Mr. Mattiece," Barr said properly. \par
\par
"The smile almost disappeared. Emil pointed beyond the pools and fountains to a large gazebo-shaped building with tall windows from floor to ceiling. Rows of perfectly manicured shrubs and flowers surrounded it.Mr. Mattiece is in his gazebo. Follow me." \par
\par
They left the sun room and walked slowly around a wading pool. Barr had a thick knot in his stomach, but he followed his little friend as if this was simply another day at the office. The sound of falling water echoed through the garden. A narrow boardwalk led to the gazebo. They stopped at the door.\par
\par
"I'm afraid you must remove your shoes," Emil said with a smile. Emil was barefoot. Barr untied his shoes and placed them next to the door.\par
\par
"Do not step on the towels," Emil said gravely. \par
\par
"The towels? \par
\par
Emil opened the door for Barr, who stepped in alone. The room was perfectly round, about fifty feet in diameter. There were three chairs and a sofa, all covered with white sheets. Thick cotton towels were on the floor in perfect little trails around the room. The sun shone brightly through skylights. A door opened, and Victor Mattiece emerged from a small room. \par
\par
Barr froze and gawked at the man. He was thin and gaunt, with long gray hair and a dirty beard. He wore only a pair of white gym shorts, and walked carefully on the towels without looking at Barr.\par
\par
"Sit over there," he said, pointing at a chair. "Don't step on the towels." \par
\par
Barr avoided the towels and took his seat. Mattiece turned his'back and faced the windows. His skin was leathery and dark bronze. His bare feet were lined with ugly veins. His toenails were long and yellow. He was crazy as hell.\par
\par
"What do you want?" he asked quietly to the windows.\par
\par
"The President sent me."\par
\par
"He did not. Fletcher Coal sent you. I doubt if the President knows you're here." \par
\par
Maybe he wasn't crazy. He spoke without moving a muscle in his body.\par
\par
"Fletcher Coal is the President's chief of staff. He sent me."\par
\par
"I know about Coal. And I know about you. And I know about your little Unit. Now, what do you want?"\par
\par
"Information."\par
\par
"Don't play games with me. What do you want?"\par
\par
"Have you read the pelican brief?" Barr asked. \par
\par
The frail body did not flinch. "Have you read it?"\par
\par
"Yes," Barr answered quickly.\par
\par
"Do you believe it to be true?"\par
\par
"Perhaps. That's why I'm here."\par
\par
"Why is Mr. Coal so concerned about the pelican brief?"\par
\par
"Because a couple of reporters have wind of it. And if it's true, then we need to know immediately."\par
\par
"Who are these reporters?"\par
\par
"Gray Grantham with the Washington Post. He picked it up first, and he knows more than anyone. He's digging hard. Coal thinks he's about to run something."\par
\par
"We can take care of him, can't we?" Mattiece said to the windows. "Who's the other one?"\par
\par
"Rifkin with the Times." \par
\par
Mattiece still had not moved an inch. Barr glanced around at the sheets and towels. Yes, he had to be crazy. The place was sanitized and smelled of rubbing alcohol. Maybe he was ill.\par
\par
"Does Mr. Coal believe it to be true?"\par
\par
"I don't know. He's very concerned about it. That's why I'm here, Mr. Mattiece. We have to know."\par
\par
"What if it's true?"\par
\par
"Then we have problems." \par
\par
Mattiece finally moved. He shifted his weight to the right leg, and folded his arms across his narrow chest. But his eyes never moved. Sand dunes and sea oats were in the distance, but not the ocean.\par
\par
"Do you know what I think?" he said quietly.\par
\par
"What?"\par
\par
"I think Coal is the problem. He gave the brief to too many people. He handed it to the CIA. He allowed you to see it. This really disturbs me." \par
\par
Barr could think of no response. It was ludicrous to imply that Coal wanted to distribute the brief. The problem is you, Mattiece. You killed the justices. You panicked and killed Callahan. You're the greedy bastard who was not content with a mere fifty million. \par
\par
Mattiece turned slowly and looked at Barr. The eyes were dark and red. He looked nothing like the photo with the Vice President, but that was seven years ago. He'd aged twenty years in the last seven, and perhaps gone off the deep end along the way.\par
\par
"You clowns in Washington are to blame for this," he said, somewhat louder. \par
\par
Barr could not look at him. "Is it true, Mr. Mattiece? That's all I want to know." \par
\par
Behind Barr, a door opened without a sound. Larry, in his socks and avoiding the towels, eased forward two steps and stopped. \par
\par
Mattiece walked on the towels to a glass door, and opened it. He looked outside and spoke softly. "Of course it's true." He walked through the door, and closed it slowly behind him. Barr watched as the idiot shuffled along a sidewalk toward the sand dunes. \par
\par
"What now? he thought. Perhaps Emil would come get him. Perhaps. \par
\par
Larry inched forward with a rope, and Barr did not hear or feel anything until it was too late. Mattiece did not want blood in his gazebo, so Larry simply broke the neck and choked him until it was over. \par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi397\qc *  *  *\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi397\qj\par
HE GAME PLAN called for her to be on this elevator at this point in the search, but she thought enough unexpected events had occurred to warrant a change in the game plan. He thought not. They had engaged in a healthy debate over this elevator ride, and here she was. He was right; this was the quickest route to Curtis Morgan. And she was right; it was a dangerous route to Curtis Morgan. But the other routes could be just as dangerous. The entire game plan was deadly. \par
\par
She wore her only dress and her only pair of heels. Gray said she looked really nice, but that was to be expected. The elevator stopped on the ninth floor, and when she walked off it there was a pain in her stomach and she could barely breathe. \par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi397\qc *  *  *\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi397\qj\par
The receptionist was across a plush lobby. The name WHITE AND BLAZEVICH covered the wall behind her in thick, brass lettering. Her knees were weak, but she made it to the receptionist, who smiled properly. It was ten minutes before five.\par
\par
"May I help you?" she asked. The nameplate proclaimed her to be Peggy Young.\par
\par
"Yes," Darby managed, clearing her throat. "I have a five o'clock appointment with Curtis Morgan. My name is Dorothy Blythe." \par
\par
The receptionist was stunned. Her mouth fell open, and she stared blankly at Darby, now Dorothy. She couldn't speak. \par
\par
Darby's heart stopped.Is something the matter?"\par
\par
"Well, no. I'm sorry. Just a moment." Peggy Young stood quickly, and disappeared in a rush. \par
\par
Run! Her heart pounded like a drum. Run! She tried to control her breathing, but she was battling hyperventilation. Her legs were rubbery. Run! \par
\par
She looked around, trying to be nonchalant as if she was just another client waiting on her lawyer. Surely they wouldn't gun her down here in the lobby of a law office. \par
\par
He came first, followed by the receptionist. He was about fifty with bushy gray hair and a terrible scowl. "Hi," he said, but only because he had to. "I'm Jarreld Schwabe, a partner here. You say you have an appointment with Curtis Morgan." \par
\par
Keep it up. "Yes. At five. Is there a problem?"\par
\par
"And your name is Dorothy Blythe?" \par
\par
Yeah, but you can call me Dot. "That's what I said. Yes. What's the matter?" She sounded genuinely irritated. \par
\par
He was inching closer. "When did you make the appointment?"\par
\par
"I don't know. About two weeks ago. I met Curtis at a party in Georgetown. He told me he was an oil and gas lawyer, and I happen to need one. I called the office here, and made an appointment. Now, will you please tell me what's going on?" She was amazed at how well these words were coming from her dry mouth.\par
\par
"Why do you need an oil and gas lawyer?"\par
\par
"I don't think I have to explain myself to you," she said, real bitchy-like. \par
\par
The elevator opened, and a man in a cheap suit approached quickly to join the conversation. Darby scowled at him. Her legs would give way just any second. \par
\par
Schwabe was really bearing down. "We don't have any record of such an appointment."\par
\par
"Then fire the appointment secretary. Do you welcome all new clients this way?" Oh, she was indignant, but Schwabe did not let up.\par
\par
"You can't see Curtis Morgan," he said.\par
\par
"And why not?" she demanded.\par
\par
"He's dead." \par
\par
The knees were jelly and about to go. A sharp pain rippled through the stomach. But, she thought quickly, it was okay to looked shocked. He was, after all, supposed to be her new lawyer.\par
\par
"I'm sorry. Why didn't anyone call me?" \par
\par
Schwabe was still suspicious. "As I said, we have no record of a Dorothy Blythe."\par
\par
"What happened to him?" she asked, stunned.\par
\par
"He was mugged a week ago. Shot by street punks, we believe." \par
\par
The guy in the cheap suit took a step closer. "Do you have any identification?"\par
\par
"Who in the hell are you?" she snapped loudly.\par
\par
"He's security," said Schwabe.\par
\par
"Security for what?" she demanded, even louder. "Is this a law firm or a prison?" \par
\par
The partner looked at the man in the cheap suit, and it was obvious neither knew exactly what to do at this point. She was very attractive, and they had upset her, and her story was somewhat believable. They relaxed a little.\par
\par
"Why don't you leave, Ms. Blythe?" Schwabe said.\par
\par
"I can't wait!" \par
\par
The security man reached to assist her. "Here," he said. \par
\par
She slapped his hand. "Touch me and I'll sue your ass first thing tomorrow morning. Get away from me!" \par
\par
This shook them a bit. She was mad and lashing out. Perhaps they were being a bit hard.\par
\par
"I'll see you down," the security man said.\par
\par
"I know how to leave. I'm amazed you clowns have any clients." She was stepping backward. Her face was red, but not from anger. It was fear. "I've got lawyers in four states, and I've never been treated like this," she yelled at them. She was in the center of the lobby. "I paid a half a million last year in legal fees, and I've got a million to pay next year, but you idiots won't get any of it." The closer she got to the elevator, the louder she yelled. She was a crazy woman. They watched her until the elevator door opened and she was gone. \par
\par
